1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,400
 "When he shall come with trumpet sound, and may I then in him be found, dressed in his

2
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:13,000
 righteousness alone, faultless I stand before his throne."

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:18,480
 The words of that beautiful modern hymn that we just heard our choir sing center us into

4
00:00:18,480 --> 00:00:23,680
 one of the most important themes of the whole Advent series that we've been doing here at

5
00:00:23,680 --> 00:00:26,000
 The Vine in 2024.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:31,400
 As I've been saying each week, we're centering Advent in this idea, not just in the arrival

7
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:37,400
 of Christ in his first coming, but also this excitement for him in his second coming.

8
00:00:37,400 --> 00:00:40,160
 In that hymn, we just hear this cry, don't we?

9
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:44,980
 When the trumpets sound, we know that Christ is going to return.

10
00:00:44,980 --> 00:00:48,200
 When he does, here's how I want to be found.

11
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:52,640
 The writer here says, "Dressed in his righteousness alone."

12
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:53,680
 It's a beautiful phrase.

13
00:00:53,680 --> 00:00:55,400
 It's one that we've sung many times here at The Vine.

14
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:59,320
 I wonder whether you've actually ever absorbed it into your spirit.

15
00:00:59,320 --> 00:01:05,480
 This thought that the author here is expressing confidence in the future arrival of Christ

16
00:01:05,480 --> 00:01:11,280
 and what will happen on that day for them, and their confidence is not found in themselves.

17
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:14,720
 It's actually a beautiful thing because I think we can overlook this really easily.

18
00:01:14,720 --> 00:01:19,760
 He's not saying on that day, "I'm going to be confident because I've lived a good life."

19
00:01:19,760 --> 00:01:23,440
 He's not saying on that day, "I'm going to have joy and confidence because I've done

20
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:25,520
 the right things."

21
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:28,120
 He says, "No, on that day, here's where my confidence is found.

22
00:01:28,120 --> 00:01:32,000
 I'm going to be dressed only in his righteousness.

23
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:38,320
 There's nothing else that I need, nothing else that I can get or gain to get me into

24
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:42,440
 heaven to get me in right relationship with him other than what he has done."

25
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:49,040
 In other words, my confidence is found in the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus.

26
00:01:49,040 --> 00:01:53,000
 The pain, the price for my sin and my brokenness, and because of that, I'm going to stand there

27
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,360
 on that day dressed in that righteousness.

28
00:01:56,360 --> 00:02:00,560
 And because I'll be dressed in that righteousness, I'll have confidence that I'll be welcomed

29
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:03,280
 into his loving arms.

30
00:02:03,280 --> 00:02:08,660
 What the song is trying to betray to us is, I think, one of the most important things

31
00:02:08,660 --> 00:02:13,320
 that Paul is saying in that passage that we've based this series in where he says, "Look,

32
00:02:13,320 --> 00:02:17,760
 we're living in a now but not yet time and there are gaps, gaps in our knowledge, gaps

33
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:20,160
 in our understanding, but we're not left alone in those gaps.

34
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:24,800
 You know, God sent some things to help lift us up in those gaps and then one of those

35
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:30,520
 things, perhaps the most critical, is exactly this confidence that we have being dressed

36
00:02:30,520 --> 00:02:33,000
 in his righteousness alone.

37
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
 It's the theme of hope."

38
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:40,160
 Oh, yes, hope.

39
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:45,680
 You know, Paul would say that the three things that remain, right, are faith, hope, and love.

40
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:48,640
 And he tells us that the greatest of these is love.

41
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:49,800
 And that's what we're going to look at next week.

42
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:54,120
 I'm going to unpack that idea of why love is the greatest next week.

43
00:02:54,120 --> 00:03:00,360
 But although it might be true that love is the greatest, I think actually it is hope

44
00:03:00,360 --> 00:03:01,840
 that is currently most needed.

45
00:03:01,840 --> 00:03:04,600
 In fact, I would put it to us like this.

46
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:09,720
 I think we're living in a world right now that is in a crisis of hope.

47
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:14,800
 I don't know what your conversations have been lately with people over lunches or coffees

48
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:21,160
 or in bars or drinks after work, but it's very easy, isn't it, to hear the doom and

49
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:28,000
 gloom and downcastness, the helplessness, the sense of hopelessness that so many are

50
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:29,760
 holding in our city.

51
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:33,760
 I think this is particularly a reality in Hong Kong because we've had a challenging

52
00:03:33,760 --> 00:03:35,400
 last five years, have we not?

53
00:03:35,400 --> 00:03:36,760
 It was really interesting.

54
00:03:36,760 --> 00:03:38,320
 I was in our market last week.

55
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:42,200
 We had a market, if you weren't here last week, this cool market outside after the services.

56
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:46,240
 And one of the stalls was run by this great organization called Eden.

57
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:51,520
 And Eden create jewelry and they raise money to help with anti-human trafficking.

58
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:55,560
 They have this card that they printed up, and when somebody comes to them in one of

59
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:58,880
 the markets that they're doing here in Hong Kong, they give the person a card.

60
00:03:58,880 --> 00:04:01,600
 And on that card it has a bunch of words.

61
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:04,360
 And these are biblical words, but they're just words there.

62
00:04:04,360 --> 00:04:08,920
 And what they say to the person is, "All of our jewelry is based on these words.

63
00:04:08,920 --> 00:04:14,480
 I want you to choose the word that resonates with you the most, the word that connects

64
00:04:14,480 --> 00:04:18,560
 to your spirit the most or the thing that you feel you need the most."

65
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:20,020
 And here's what they told me last week.

66
00:04:20,020 --> 00:04:24,280
 They said out of all of the young people in Hong Kong that come forward in the store and

67
00:04:24,280 --> 00:04:28,800
 they give that card to, the one word they choose, the one thing that they feel like

68
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:31,160
 they need the most, can you guess what it is?

69
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:33,960
 The word hope.

70
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:36,040
 The word hope.

71
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:39,440
 And it's not just the young people of our city that are struggling with this.

72
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:44,120
 I think all of us are in some ways wrestling with, is this still the place we want to be

73
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:45,120
 in?

74
00:04:45,120 --> 00:04:47,200
 Is Hong Kong going to recover?

75
00:04:47,200 --> 00:04:50,440
 Are there going to be some signs at some point where we'll feel like everything's going to

76
00:04:50,440 --> 00:04:51,440
 go well?

77
00:04:51,440 --> 00:04:52,440
 Are rents going to come back down?

78
00:04:52,440 --> 00:04:53,800
 Is money going to go back up?

79
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:55,080
 Am I going to get a job?

80
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:56,920
 Is everything going to get settled again?

81
00:04:56,920 --> 00:05:00,960
 And there's this sort of sense of helplessness or hopelessness in our city.

82
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:01,960
 And here's the reality.

83
00:05:01,960 --> 00:05:04,400
 It's not just our city.

84
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:05,640
 It's the whole world at the moment.

85
00:05:05,640 --> 00:05:10,720
 I mean, if we just lift our heads up a little bit and look at BBC or CNN or any of the other

86
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:14,200
 news outlets and we begin to see what's going on around the world, we can see that that

87
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:19,960
 sense of helplessness and hopelessness is pervasive in our world right now.

88
00:05:19,960 --> 00:05:20,960
 And here's the thing.

89
00:05:20,960 --> 00:05:26,760
 There's actually a lot of good evidence to suggest that we don't have much hope right

90
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:27,760
 now.

91
00:05:27,760 --> 00:05:31,720
 I mean, if you just look at some of the economic disparities that we're seeing in the world

92
00:05:31,720 --> 00:05:34,200
 right now, the rich are getting richer and the poor are getting poorer.

93
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:38,880
 And that gap is widening more now than in any other time in history.

94
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,200
 Have a think about exploitation.

95
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:43,280
 There's more human trafficking than ever before.

96
00:05:43,280 --> 00:05:46,640
 There's more forced labor migration than ever before.

97
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:51,280
 The poor and the vulnerable are being exploited like they've never been before.

98
00:05:51,280 --> 00:05:56,440
 Look at the realities of movement, migration, and displacement in the world.

99
00:05:56,440 --> 00:05:59,760
 Asylum seekers and refugees, something dear to our hearts here at the Vine, they're struggling

100
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:02,560
 around globally more than ever before.

101
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:05,800
 And when you begin to put all this together, you realize that there is more violence in

102
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:07,840
 our world, it seems, than ever before.

103
00:06:07,840 --> 00:06:09,360
 There's more wars that are happening.

104
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:14,240
 And wars, here's the thing, when wars happen, it is always the innocent that seems to suffer

105
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:15,880
 most, like children.

106
00:06:15,880 --> 00:06:19,560
 And we've seen that over the last couple of years, perhaps more than ever.

107
00:06:19,560 --> 00:06:23,400
 And when we weigh this all up, it's not a surprise, perhaps, that there's a sense of

108
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:26,200
 helplessness on us, a sense of hopelessness.

109
00:06:26,200 --> 00:06:27,960
 And I want to be honest with you.

110
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:29,720
 Here's what I hear at the Vine.

111
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:36,080
 I hear the same kind of helplessness amongst us in conversations I'm having with you, in

112
00:06:36,080 --> 00:06:37,820
 conversations you're having with our pastors.

113
00:06:37,820 --> 00:06:42,920
 We know that that sense of helplessness, that sense of hopelessness, is even pervasive into

114
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:48,400
 the church, which is really interesting because surely the church should be filled with people

115
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:53,280
 who are the most hopeful, but the reality are, if you're anything like me, you struggle

116
00:06:53,280 --> 00:06:55,160
 with this too.

117
00:06:55,160 --> 00:07:01,280
 But it isn't always easy, is it, to find hope within us.

118
00:07:01,280 --> 00:07:05,520
 And despite everything that's happening and all the feelings that we're feeling and the

119
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:09,680
 realities of the evidence that we're seeing, I want to call you over the next 30 minutes

120
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:12,720
 or so to take a stand against despair.

121
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:14,600
 Come on, church.

122
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:21,200
 If there's ever a community of people around this world that in a time of a hope crisis

123
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:26,880
 should be rising up with an alternative way of seeing the world, an alternative narrative

124
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:31,200
 of saying that there's actually something better, that there is something to hope for,

125
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:35,640
 there is something to long for, that it isn't all doom and gloom, that the reality might

126
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:40,440
 be that there's evidence around us that would suggest a certain path, but there is always

127
00:07:40,440 --> 00:07:41,440
 hope.

128
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:48,120
 If it should be anyone, shouldn't it be the church at Christmas?

129
00:07:48,120 --> 00:07:52,560
 So why is our voice silent?

130
00:07:52,560 --> 00:07:59,080
 I think our voice is largely silent because if you're anything like me, along the way

131
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:03,020
 you've been burnt by hope.

132
00:08:03,020 --> 00:08:06,960
 Maybe you come in today and just the very idea that I'm speaking on hope raises some

133
00:08:06,960 --> 00:08:09,000
 complex feelings for you.

134
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:14,640
 Perhaps you're sitting in here right now and you've had a diagnosis this week, or something's

135
00:08:14,640 --> 00:08:20,720
 happened in your family, or it's been challenging for you and you're facing what you're facing

136
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:24,800
 in an uncertain future and you're wrestling with that.

137
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:29,160
 Perhaps there's some of you, you put a lot of hope before in a changed relationship,

138
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:32,200
 but that relationship didn't seem to change.

139
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:36,960
 Or you put your hope in perhaps a debt to get paid off, but no matter how hard you've

140
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:40,160
 worked it hasn't seemed like you've been able to pay off that debt.

141
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:44,400
 Perhaps you put your hope in resolving a dispute that you've been having with a loved one,

142
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:48,400
 and no matter how hard you've tried it seems to get worse, not better.

143
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:52,080
 Perhaps for you, you've tried to lead some people to faith this year and they haven't

144
00:08:52,080 --> 00:08:55,360
 given their lives to Jesus and you're wondering what that's all about.

145
00:08:55,360 --> 00:09:00,160
 All of us perhaps have a story where we've put so much stock and faith into this thing

146
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:05,080
 called hope and it seems like it's flimsy, it's intangible.

147
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:09,640
 It doesn't seem like it's actually worked out for us and we've been so burnt by hope

148
00:09:09,640 --> 00:09:16,160
 that even the idea of hope carries with it this pain in us and we're like, "What has

149
00:09:16,160 --> 00:09:20,120
 hope ever done for me?"

150
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:25,440
 And perhaps because we're wrestling with that, the idea of having hope seems foreign to us

151
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:29,920
 and you're sitting there and you're saying to yourself, "I don't even think that it's

152
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:38,000
 worth me getting excited about something that seems so intangible."

153
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,920
 I think the reason why we Christians struggle with this, I want you to follow this, I think

154
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:46,840
 the reason why we Christians struggle with this is because there is this tension between

155
00:09:46,840 --> 00:09:53,080
 the good idea of hope and our present reality or experience with it.

156
00:09:53,080 --> 00:09:57,640
 And when those two things don't seem to add up a lot, it creates a bit of a tension within

157
00:09:57,640 --> 00:09:58,720
 us.

158
00:09:58,720 --> 00:10:02,320
 But I want to put it to you that the reason why these two things don't add up much for

159
00:10:02,320 --> 00:10:06,720
 us as Christians, the good idea of hope and our present reality with it, is because I

160
00:10:06,720 --> 00:10:11,760
 think as Christians, and I would say this boldly, I think as the global church, we've

161
00:10:11,760 --> 00:10:16,600
 actually defined hope completely wrong.

162
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:21,160
 Let me tell you a little bit about how society, how the world defines hope and how hope is

163
00:10:21,160 --> 00:10:23,640
 used mostly in an everyday context.

164
00:10:23,640 --> 00:10:25,200
 So it would be something like this.

165
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:31,880
 Hope is an expressed, desired, positive outcome that is uncertain.

166
00:10:31,880 --> 00:10:32,960
 Let me give you an example.

167
00:10:32,960 --> 00:10:37,480
 My beautiful daughter Mia, who's 14 years old, she hopes that we will get her an iPad

168
00:10:37,480 --> 00:10:40,520
 for Christmas.

169
00:10:40,520 --> 00:10:43,360
 And what she really means by that is this.

170
00:10:43,360 --> 00:10:50,240
 I hope that my mom and dad will dig into their bank account and buy me an iPad, but I have

171
00:10:50,240 --> 00:10:53,080
 absolutely no certainty whether they will do that or not.

172
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:56,680
 It's just a hoped for, desired outcome that is uncertain.

173
00:10:56,680 --> 00:10:58,400
 Are you following this?

174
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:01,080
 And my daughter is very smart because it is uncertain.

175
00:11:01,080 --> 00:11:04,520
 Okay, I just want you to know that she's not in the service.

176
00:11:04,520 --> 00:11:07,000
 That is a false hope, okay?

177
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,560
 Have you seen how expensive iPads are?

178
00:11:09,560 --> 00:11:11,560
 That is not happening, all right?

179
00:11:11,560 --> 00:11:12,800
 Don't tell her that if you see her later.

180
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:15,000
 It's not happening.

181
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:19,520
 Or maybe you're sitting there and you're like, "I hope Pastor Andrew only preaches for 15

182
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:21,320
 minutes today."

183
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:25,560
 What you're really saying is, "I would prefer a short service today because I want to get

184
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:30,040
 out there into the bake sale as quickly as possible, and I hope that he's short, but

185
00:11:30,040 --> 00:11:32,920
 actually I've been coming to the Vine for a while, and I know that he's not going to

186
00:11:32,920 --> 00:11:33,920
 be short at all."

187
00:11:33,920 --> 00:11:37,080
 So, it's weird.

188
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:41,800
 This hope that we use and we talk about so often, this is actually how we define it and

189
00:11:41,800 --> 00:11:42,800
 how we use it.

190
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:49,000
 In other words, hope is based in the reality that something is uncertain, but I hope that

191
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 it will work out.

192
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:51,640
 I don't know if it will or not.

193
00:11:51,640 --> 00:11:55,480
 The facts don't necessarily suggest it will or not, but I'm just going to kind of like

194
00:11:55,480 --> 00:12:00,720
 throw a dart at a dart board and hope that I might get that 12 or triple 12 or whatever

195
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:02,840
 it is, hope that things will work out.

196
00:12:02,840 --> 00:12:03,840
 I'm not sure.

197
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:04,940
 I'm not certain.

198
00:12:04,940 --> 00:12:09,000
 It's a bit of a crack shoot, but we're going to see if this thing plays out okay.

199
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:13,920
 And when it doesn't, darn it, I hoped again and it failed me.

200
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:16,240
 Are you with me, church?

201
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:22,600
 And because we have come to define hope within a Christian context in the same way that the

202
00:12:22,600 --> 00:12:30,200
 world defines hope, it's not a surprise that the church has lost its voice.

203
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:35,080
 I think we actually ask this question mostly in church and it's this, "Why would I put

204
00:12:35,080 --> 00:12:45,360
 my faith in something as flimsy, as uncertain, as doubtful as a thing like hope?"

205
00:12:45,360 --> 00:12:49,000
 And because of that, here's what I've noticed.

206
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,320
 Christians don't talk about hope.

207
00:12:52,320 --> 00:12:57,760
 And we don't talk about hope because we don't want to set anybody up for failure because

208
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:02,200
 we've failed this way a lot and we don't want to push that on anyone else.

209
00:13:02,200 --> 00:13:06,780
 So we downplay the reality of hope in church contexts.

210
00:13:06,780 --> 00:13:10,400
 You got to understand that the Bible does not downplay hope.

211
00:13:10,400 --> 00:13:14,700
 In fact, the Bible mentions hope over 600 times.

212
00:13:14,700 --> 00:13:17,640
 It is mentioned in almost every single book in the Bible.

213
00:13:17,640 --> 00:13:22,960
 When you get to the New Testament, the idea of hope is mentioned every two or three pages

214
00:13:22,960 --> 00:13:25,040
 throughout the whole of the Old Testament.

215
00:13:25,040 --> 00:13:30,440
 The Bible has a lot to say about hope, so why are we silent?

216
00:13:30,440 --> 00:13:32,240
 I went to seminary for four years.

217
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:35,280
 I never did a class on hope.

218
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:36,760
 Faith got it nailed.

219
00:13:36,760 --> 00:13:38,040
 Did lots of classes on faith.

220
00:13:38,040 --> 00:13:41,040
 Love, oh my gosh, we talked about love all the time.

221
00:13:41,040 --> 00:13:42,840
 We never once mentioned hope.

222
00:13:42,840 --> 00:13:47,880
 In fact, the only time the word hope was mentioned in my seminary over four years was when the

223
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:53,160
 teacher was trying to call out the person whose first name was hope.

224
00:13:53,160 --> 00:13:57,240
 That was the only time that I ever heard that word in seminary.

225
00:13:57,240 --> 00:14:00,560
 We don't talk about hope because we've come to misunderstand it.

226
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:02,240
 We're defining it in a wrong way.

227
00:14:02,240 --> 00:14:06,280
 And because we don't want to set anybody up to fail or into some uncertainty, we've kind

228
00:14:06,280 --> 00:14:08,000
 of closed our mouth about it.

229
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,080
